Citations
Date: 8/4/1882
Source: Wanganui Chronicle
Author:
Vol / Page: 2
Edition:
Quote: AT some time in the future, when the land question shall have been satisfactorily settled by the wiping out of freeholds, and by making every man, woman, and child in the colony a compulsory state tenant of fifty acres of land, with a "pay as you please" clause in the leases, and the cruelty of an eviction swept away for ever, the position of the people will be somewhat different from what it is under the present crude and unsatisfactory system in which the relations of landlord and tenant, and of master and man, if not in full force, retain at least a portion of their ancient vitality.
Notes:

Date: 13/7/1910
Source: Grey River Argus
Author:
Vol / Page: 6
Edition:
Quote: The Farmers' Union Conference passed resolutoions [sic] that state tenants should have the right of acquiring freehold, and that the Government be urged to spend GBP100,000 annually on re-afforestation, the money to be spent either by Lands Departments or in encouraging private individuals to plant suitable trees, and that the Maori lands should pay the same rates and taxes as Europeans.
